Sentence-String: The common regime of eccentric exercise in use for Achilles tendinopathy is somewhat arduous and compliance issues can arise.
This is the first study to investigate the effectiveness of a regime of fewer exercise sessions combined with photobiomodulation for the treatment of Achilles tendinopathy.
A double blind randomized controlled trial and intention-to-treat analysis were performed.
Eighty participants, 18–65 years with Achilles tendinopathy and symptoms for longer than 3 months, were included in the trial.
Participants randomized into one of four groups; 1 (Placebo + Ex Regime 1) or 2 (Laser + Ex Regime 1) or 3 (Placebo + Ex Regime 2) or 4 (Laser + Ex Regime 2).
The primary outcome measure was the Victorian Institute of Sports Assessment-Achilles (VISA-A) questionnaire.
Outcomes were collected at baseline, week 4 and week 12.
Sixteen participants were lost to follow-up at 12 weeks, 4 of which due to adverse reactions.
As per intention to treat, missing data were imputed, 80 participants were included in the final analysis.
For VISA-A at 12 weeks, group 4 achieved significant gains over the other 3 groups: group 1 (18.5 [9.1, 27.9]), group 2 (10.4 [1.5, 19.2]), group 3 (11.3 [3.0, 19.6]).
There was a moderate effect size in favour of exercise twice per week (7.2 [−1.8, 16.2], ES .7).
Twice-daily exercise sessions are not necessary as equivalent results can be obtained with two exercise sessions per week.
The addition of photobiomodulation as adjunct to exercise can bring added benefit.
Dose response Exercise therapy Laser therapy Rehabilitation
A recent study estimated the incidence of Achilles tendinopathy in the 21–60-year age group as 235/100,000.

Although the exact cause of pain in tendinopathy remains elusive, it is generally accepted that tendinopathy is the result of a failure of one of two processes: the healing response, or the normal turnover/remodelling response.
Two interactive hypotheses have been postulated to explain the failure of the tendon to repair or remodel itself: the biomechanical hypothesis and the biochemical hypothesis.
Tendon-loading programmes have emerged as the treatment of choice for Achilles tendinopathy.
Mechanotransduction is thought to be the mechanism behind such effects .

Cells under mechanical stress respond by producing enzymes and proteins that enhance the remodelling process, resulting in increased collagen synthesis and improved viscoelastic properties and these effects can last more than 72 h.
Different approaches to loading are evident in the literature, heavy slow resistance training, heavy load eccentric exercise, and eccentric to concentric progression to name but a few.

A review of tendon-loading programmes that included 32 studies reported variation in the frequency of prescribed exercise sessions, but the scientific rationale behind these protocols is often lacking, especially with regard to dose/response.
Also, the fact that mechanotransduction can also be detrimental when the loads become too excessive is a ground to determine the optimal loading regime.

Depending upon the outcome measures employed, it is difficult to conclude that any form of exercise is superior to another as any loading seems to produce positive outcomes; a fact supported by a recent study by Beyer et al.
who compared heavy slow resistance exercise with eccentric exercise for Achilles tendon patients.
The most common regime of eccentric exercise for Achilles tendinopathy advocates twice-daily sessions, every day for 12 weeks; something patients find laborious and issues of compliance arise.

Two recent systematic reviews on exercise protocols, because of the heterogeneity of included studies, and lack of reporting of compliance, failed to make any definitive conclusions with regard to the most effective regime.
Given the evidence for the duration of enhanced remodelling after eccentric exercise, it is difficult to justify the twice-daily regime, and yet it is utilized often.

Laser-induced photobiomodulation (PBM) has been shown to induce changes in membrane permeability, stimulation of cytokine reactions, release of growth factors, up-regulation of ATP, NO and REDOX signalling, and therefore increased metabolism and cell proliferation .

Arising from these effects, important benefits in the treatment of tendinopathy are decreased inflammation, increased angiogenesis, and increased fibroblast activity, leading in turn to increased collagen production and to increased tensile strength and decreased pain.
Therefore, laser therapy has the potential to enhance the repair and remodelling process required for the resolution of tendinopathy.
However, evidence from clinical trials has provided mixed results, and the optimum dose has yet to be defined.
This is the first study to examine the effects of two exercise sessions per week against that of the 14 sessions advocated by Alfredson.
In addition, the effectiveness of combining laser therapy to these exercise protocols was assessed.

The objectives of this study were to determine the most clinically effective loading regime for Achilles tendinopathy and to determine if any extra benefit can be gained from adding laser therapy in combination with exercise.
The study design conforms to the CONSORT statement for conducting randomized controlled trials.

A prospective randomized clinical trial, with assessor blinding and intention-to-treat analysis, was performed at a University Physical Therapy Clinic, utilizing a 2 × 2 factorial design comparing four groups.
The primary analysis was performed at 3 months, and the main outcome measure will be the Victorian Institute of Sports Assessment-Achilles (VISA-A) questionnaire.
The outcomes at 52 weeks will be used to describe the long-term results in a future analysis.
Blinding ensured that the assessor and participants were not aware of who received placebo or active laser.
Ethical approval was granted on 1 August 2013 by the Health and Disability Ethics Committee of New Zealand, ref;13/NTA/102.
The trial was registered with the Australia New Zealand Clinical Trials Register (ANZCTR), ref; ACTRN12613000662763.
Participants were screened against the inclusion/exclusion criteria by the principal investigator.
After informed consent was given, randomization occurred prior to assessment of all outcome measures.
Thereafter, participants commenced the intervention/s required by the group in to which they were allocated.
Each participant was seen by the same physical therapist for treatment interventions; and by the same (separate) assessor for evaluation of outcome measures.
In addition to the VISA-A, subjects were asked to complete compliance logs to report their adherence to the exercise regime, where they recorded the number of exercise sessions they had completed.
Participants who were lost to follow-up had their data collected to the drop-out point, and this data was included in an “intention-to-treat analysis”.

Patients 18–65 years with a diagnosis of Achilles tendinopathy greater than 3 months duration based upon accepted diagnostic criteria, and assessed by an experienced physical therapist or physician; and who had not received treatment within the last 3 months; VISA-A score <80.

The exclusion criteria include contraindications to laser therapy to the area of the Achilles tendon; co-morbid musculoskeletal or serious conditions which may have confounded treatment or anticipated recovery; NSAIDs use; steroid injections or surgery for the condition; insertional tendinopathy or bursitis (retrocalcaneal or Achilles; determined by clinical examination); neurological signs; adverse neural tension affecting the sciatic or sural nerves; VISA-A score >80; symptoms less than 3 months.
Participants were block randomized into one of four groups by asking them to select any one of 80 identical opaque sealed envelopes.
The groups were 1 (Placebo + Ex Regime 1) or 2 (PBM + Ex Regime 1) or 3 (Placebo + Ex Regime 2) or 4 (PBM + Ex Regime 2), based upon a computer-generated random number list.
Neither the principal investigator nor the participant had any knowledge of which group received the active laser treatment, allocation was concealed.
Laser protocol (see eProtocol)
The device used was a Lightforce EX unit (Litecure LLC, Newark, NJ, USA).
Laser treatment was delivered with the patient prone, their foot over the end of the treatment plinth, and the ankle plantar-grade.
The scanning method with the probe in contact with the skin was used to apply the laser treatment in a standardized fashion to the Achilles tendon.
Treatment was given two times per week for 4 weeks with 48 h between applications.
The tendon was irradiated with a sweeping motion from the calcaneus to 10 cm proximal on the medial, lateral, and posterior aspects of the tendon (Fig.

The parameters were wavelength 810 and 980 nm (fixed ratio 810:980 of 20:80); 10 W output power, pulsed 100 Hz giving average power output of 5 W; spot size 3 cm2; for 30 s, 150 J delivered to each aspect of the tendon, for a total time of 1:30 min and total energy delivered of 450 J at energy density 6.66 J/cm2 (see eProtocol for dosage calculations).
Laser or placebo laser treatment was performed prior to the exercise sessions during the first 4 weeks.
Laser application: The tendon was irradiated with a sweeping motion from the calcaneus to 10 cm proximal on the medial, lateral, and posterior aspects of the tendon
Exercise protocol (see eProtocol)

Participants were instructed to perform one of two unilateral heavy load eccentric plantar flexion training programmes lasting 12 weeks; regime 1 was twice per day, 7 days per week, or regime 2 which was once per day, twice per week.
Instructions were to go ahead even if they experience pain, and they were only allowed to stop if the pain became disabling (>4/10 on the pain scale).
When participants could complete the exercise without pain they were instructed to increase the loading by adding extra weight.
Running was allowed, but only if it could be performed with mild discomfort and not pain.

The primary outcome measure was the validated VISA-A questionnaire; secondary outcomes were the Numeric Pain Rating Scale (NPRS) and measurements of tendon thickness taken in the sagittal plane at the thickest part of the tendon using a diagnostic ultrasound.
All of the outcomes were measured by a blinded assessor before treatment 1, at the end of the laser treatment phase (4 weeks) and at the end of the exercise phase (12 weeks).
The primary outcome time point was at the 12-week point.
Analysis was conducted blinded to group allocation on an intention-to-treat basis using SPSS statistical software v20 (SPSS Inc, Chicago, Illinois).
Differences between groups at baseline with respect to demographic and clinical variables were examined to assess the effectiveness of randomization.
The general linear model was used to test the effect of treatment between groups for the primary outcome.
Multiple imputation was used to replace missing data following intention-to-treat protocols.
Bonferroni adjustment for post hoc multiple pairwise comparisons was utilized.
Effect size (Cohen’s d) was calculated for the pairwise comparisons at the primary end point using actual mean values.
From previous pilot study data [40] using the change scores at 12 weeks and the participants’ reported satisfaction, sample size calculations were obtained.

Assuming a significance level of alpha = 0.05 (two-sided) and a standard deviation of 20.25, an RCT with a sample size of 16 participants in each treatment group using two follow-up measurements will have a power of greater than 0.8 to detect a difference of 16 on the VISA-A.
Allowing for 20 % drop-outs, 20 participants per group were required.

This number was also sufficient to assess the interaction of laser and eccentric exercise as power calculations for this interaction with the 2 × 2 design, moderate effect size (0.5) and alpha set at 0.5 gave a sample size of 17 per group.
Between 19 August 2013 and 27 March 2014, 108 people contacted the clinic for information.
The first 80 participants that met the inclusion criteria and gave informed consent were recruited into the study, and the 12-week data collection ceased on 25 June 2014.

Multiple imputation used to replace missing data for final analysis

Six participants complained of delayed onset muscle soreness (DOMS) within the first week of starting treatment, three of these withdrew from the study; otherwise, no other adverse reactions were reported.
There was no statistically significant difference between groups for any of the outcome measures reported at initial evaluation; demographics and baseline characteristics are displayed in Table 1.
Analysis of the patterns of missing values showed that 4.6 % of data was missing at random; this data was replaced using multiple imputation for the final analysis.
Baseline demographics and characteristics
Table 2 displays the within group results for VISA-A and NPRS scores at the specified time points.

At the primary end point, all groups had improved their VISA-A scores by greater than the minimal clinical important difference (MCID) reported previously and changes were comparable with similar studies.
The pairwise comparisons of the main outcome measures between groups are displayed in Table 3.

The group/time interaction showed a statistically significant difference in favour of the group that received laser as an adjunct to exercise regime 2 compared to the other three groups (F 1 2.742, p = .013).
Outcomes within groups at specified time points
Differences in main outcome measures between groups

Tests of between subject effects demonstrated tendon thickness reduced significantly over the course of the intervention (p < .001), but there was no significant difference in these changes between groups at 12 weeks (p > .99).
The mean and standard deviation (mm) for group 1 reduced from 8.0 (2.0) to 7.3 (1.9); group 2 from 8.0 (1.8) to 7.6 (1.7); group 3 from 7.6 (1.5) to 6.4 (1.5); group 4 from 8.6 (1.9) to 7.0 (1.7).
Compliance logs were returned by 46 of the participants after the 12-week intervention phase.
The maximum number of prescribed exercise sessions for groups 1 and 2 was 168; for groups 3 and 4, it was 24 (Table 4).
Compliance to the exercise regimes at 12 weeks

The objectives of this study were to determine the most clinical effective regime of eccentric exercise for Achilles tendinopathy and to assess if added benefit could be achieved from the use of laser as adjunct to the exercise.

This is the first study to show that the somewhat arduous regime advocated by the Alfredson protocol is not necessary to attain meaningful changes in pain and function as comparable scores were displayed by the groups performing only two exercise sessions per week.
In fact a moderate effect size of 0.7 was calculated in favour of the reduced regime over the Alfredson protocol (Table 3).

The addition of laser to the treatment provided additional gains, but only the group receiving the combination of laser with the regime of two exercise sessions per week demonstrated statistically significant improvements over the other three groups with effect sizes ranging from large to very large (Table 3).

Until recently heavy load eccentric exercises have become the treatment of choice for Achilles tendinopathy and are widely used both in clinical practice and research despite weak evidence to support isolating the eccentric component.
They are often used in other trials as the “usual care” or common intervention across treatment and control groups where the investigators are assessing other therapies, i.e.
prolotherapy, platelet-rich plasma injection, extra corporeal shock wave therapy .
A recent study in Scotland is one of the few that have attempted to find a dose-response relationship for these exercises.

In the Scottish study, the Alfredson protocol was matched against a “do as tolerated” protocol where participants still were required to exercise twice per day but could reduce the number of repetitions.
reported that there was no statistically significant difference between the groups at 6 weeks.
These results are comparable with the present study where the exercises were carried out for 12 weeks, a common length of time for the intervention in previous studies.

Loading of the tendon with exercise stimulates the remodelling process, and these effects peak at 72 h post exercise; thus, justification for twice-daily sessions or three times per week sessions is lacking.

In the present study, two groups performed exercises reduced to one session per day on 2 days of the week and instructed to leave 2–3 days between exercise sessions, thus gaining the full benefit of mechanotransduction before once more stimulating the process.

A recent study comparing the common twice per day eccentric loading regime against a three times per week heavy slow resistance regime also reported comparable positive outcomes between groups, but failed to provide the rationale behind the frequency of loading sessions.

In clinical trials, the evidence for laser for tendinopathy has been mixed, with advocates extolling the importance of the correct dose, and guidelines are available that stipulate less than 100 mW/cm2 power density for Achilles tendons.
The controversy exists in the interpretation of density; should power and energy density be calculated over the spot size of the laser beam, or over the area to be treated?
There is no consensus over this argument.

Therefore, in the present study, parameters were chosen that exceeded this limit… 1.67 W/cm2 over the beam area, or calculated over the area to be treated, 222 mW/cm2, and for 30 s equating to 6.66 J/cm2.

Regardless of breaking this arbitrary limit, the outcomes as measured on the VISA-A and NPRS demonstrated positive results, with both laser groups exhibiting greater gains than the other two groups (Table 3).

The culmination of benefit from the reduced exercise regimen allowing the remodelling process to peak, combined with the effects of the laser, discussed in the previous paragraphs, may explain the large differences in change scores shown between group 4 and group 1 (Table 3).

Interestingly, at the end of the treatment phase with laser (4 weeks) differences in VISA-A and NPRS scores between groups were unremarkable, but at the 12-week follow-up meaningful changes occurred for group 4.

This phenomenon of greater gains at longer term follow-up for laser treatment compared to directly at the end of the treatment phase has recently been reported from a meta-analysis of laser acupuncture studies for musculoskeletal pain, but the exact mechanism for this has yet to be elucidated.
To the best of the authors’ knowledge, this is the first study to use such high power density and report positive outcomes.
Adherence to such an arduous exercise regime as the Alfredson protocol where patients are instructed to exercise with pain and perform multiple sessions daily will always raise issues of compliance.
Two systematic reviews specifically looking at the dose/response question included 15 articles between them with 8 studies reporting on the exact protocol advocated by Alfredson.
Both reviews concluded that there is no standard method for reporting compliance and often it is not reported at all; therefore, recommendations on the most efficacious regime could not be made.
From the studies that do report compliance, no attempt was made to define the relationship between exercise parameters and outcomes.

Using data from the returned compliance logs, in the present study for groups that performed the reduced exercise regime, compliance was 100 %; for groups that were prescribed the Alfredson protocol compliance only reached approximately 70 %.
Tendon thickness was measured in the sagittal plane at the thickest part of the tendon.
Within groups, the tendon thickness reduced after 12 weeks of intervention, a finding that has been reported in other studies.
This outcome measure was not considered during power calculations for the present study, and this should be considered when interpreting this finding.
It was beyond the scope of this study to define the relationship between the amounts of exercise completed to the change in outcome measures over the intervention period.
No attempt was made to evaluate tendon structure or mechanical properties apart from tendon thickness in the sagittal plane; this study was not powered to answer these questions.

Future studies could address these questions as well as removing the standard follow-up point at 12 weeks; then the question of whether exercise regime 2 with laser may accelerate recovery could be answered.

This study has added to the evidence in two ways, in expanding the effective treatment window of laser parameters and reporting that clinical benefits can be achieved with eccentric exercise with far less endeavour on the part of the patient.
Two sessions of heavy load eccentric exercise per week for 12 weeks can be recommended.
Photobiomodulation using the parameters stated above as adjunct to eccentric exercise can induce added benefit at 12 weeks.
